WRITING.TEXT:
 Planned on going to an Estate Sale near me which had a TON of items I could flip. Was late getting there and found upon my arrival a line of 120+ people. When I finally got in the house, everything I wanted was GONE, and it was uncomfortably tight; house was from 1844. I still ended up purchasing eight items for $40.00 and plan to flip them soon. 

* (1) Tin Type photo of a woman sitting on a chair (great condition, no frame, but she is attractive and will sell); 
* (1) Personal/Pocket *Holy Bible* in excellent condition from 1864;
* (1) Texas Rangers Vintage "Rangers" Large Patch;
* (1) *My Father, Mark Twain* by Clara Clemens (Mark Twain's Daughter) 1st Ed. 2nd Printing and it is SIGNED by Clara...could be the best item of the lot;
* (1) *Manual on the Constitution* by Marietta College President Andrews in 1874 (I will keep this one; I'm a law school graduate and collect anything "law related.")
* (2) U.S Army Remembrance Pillow Shams from Camp Phillips, Kansas   Camp Forrest, Tennessee; 
* (1) Malta, Montana Wild West Pillow Sham (Great graphics; Man riding a bucking bronco).

I bought the pillow shams out of fear of passing them up; I thought they were flags. I couldn't do my normal eBay search because there was SO MANY people around me. The house easily had 50-100 people in it. In the upstairs bedroom I found a floorboard that looked to be intentionally cut to be removable. I popped it up and there WAS a space for hiding items, but there wasn't any items in the space; super glad I found it.
